---
import Base from '../layouts/Base.astro';
import { site, href } from '../site';
---
<Base title={`About — ${site.name}`} description="How Lede works: read everything, keep almost nothing, explain what's left.">
  <article class="article measure">
    <header class="article__head">
      <span class="label">Colophon</span>
      <h1 class="article__title">Read everything. Keep almost nothing.</h1>
    </header>
    <div class="prose">
      <p>There is too much to read, and most of it isn’t worth the time. {site.name} exists to fix the ratio. It watches the places technology, AI, and the sciences actually break first — over a thousand of them, from the labs and the front pages to the long tail of practitioner blogs — and surfaces the handful of things that matter, with a clear account of <em>why</em>.</p>

      <h2>How it works</h2>
      <p>Every cycle, {site.name} pulls from its full roll of <strong>verified sources</strong>: aggregators, research feeds, company and lab blogs, newsletters, and the deep bench of individual engineers who quietly write the best things on the internet. Items are clustered, so a story that surfaces across many independent sources rises; the rest settle. Everything that survives gets scored.</p>
      <p>The finalists get read — actually read — by a language model briefed to be a ruthless editor: Sonnet scores relevance, pulls the load-bearing details, and writes the one line that tells you whether to care. Marketing dressed as news, thin rewrites, and benchmark theater get cut. Then Opus writes the editions, under a style guide it doesn’t get to argue with.</p>
      <p>The editions run on a fixed clock. A <strong>daily brief</strong> lands weekday mornings. The <strong>weekly digest</strong>, the flagship, lands Friday. Behind those sit the monthly review, the quarterly report, and the year — each one a longer lens on the same pipeline.</p>

      <h2>Principles</h2>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Primary sources first.</strong> The paper, the repo, the filing — not the press release about them. When the original is walled, the best free read is found and linked as backup.</li>
        <li><strong>Why, not just what.</strong> Anyone can list links. Each pick says what it means and who should care.</li>
        <li><strong>Unbiased by construction.</strong> Claims are attributed as claims. Disagreement is shown, not smoothed over.</li>
        <li><strong>Your data stays yours.</strong> No account, no tracking, no inbox. Your <a href={href('/preferences/')}>reading preferences</a> — theme, type size, density, which sections you want, how much of the machinery to show — live in this browser and nowhere else.</li>
        <li><strong>No inbox required.</strong> {site.name} lives in your feed reader. Subscribe to everything, only the digests, one cadence, or a single section.</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>Subscribe</h2>
      <p>Point any RSS reader at <a href={href('/rss.xml')}>the full feed</a>, take <a href={href('/digests/rss.xml')}>the digests alone</a>, or pick a cadence or channel from <a href={href('/feeds/')}>the feed directory</a>. New picks arrive as they’re curated; the editions, on their clock.</p>
    </div>
    <a class="back" href={href('/')}>← Front page</a>
  </article>
</Base>
